	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				<img class="inlineimg" src="images/icons/icon1.gif" alt="Default" border="0" />
				
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#000000" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<i>Originally posted by Dakkin </i><br />
<b>Same appears to work when taunting mobs off people who've been offtanking for a while.  Taunt-and-hit on its own often doesn't help, but successful taunt followed by a good aggro spell works every time.<br />
<br />
Not sure why this is. </b>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> <br />
Because of the way taunt works.   A successful taunt is (current_highest_aggro)+1.<br />
<br />
If you taunt successfully and attack, your aggro would be (former_highest_aggro)+1+(melee_round).<br />
<br />
If you were to replace melee_round with a high aggro spell, like fear or CD, your total aggro would be substantially higher than if you just taunted and attacked.<br />
<br />
<b><u>Example 1</u>:</b><br />
Paladin offtanks mob, builds 3000 hate<br />
SK taunts successfully, now has 3001 hate<br />
Paladin swings a round of melee, has 3100 hate<br />
SK swings a round of melee, has 3101 hate<br />
<b>Result</b>:  aggro ping-pong<br />
<br />
<b><u>Example 2</u>:</b><br />
Paladin offtanks mob, builds 3000 hate<br />
SK taunts successfully, now has 3001 hate<br />
Paladin swings a round of melee, has 3100 hate<br />
SK casts fear, has 3500 hate<br />
<b>Result</b>:  solid aggro lead<br />
<br />
Numbers are of course hypothetical, but do you see the point?</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
